      <h3>Micro Loans</h3>
      <p>
        A business supplies propane to customers throughout a state and owns a fleet of trucks.  The business contacts a banker and arranges a new business bank loan. In order to get a better rate on their business bank loan, they choose a asset based loan and put up the fleet of trucks as collateral for a new shipment of propane at an interest rate of 5.75% Annual Percentage Rate (APR) until the loan is paid off.  If the business is unable to pay the loan off, the bank gets the fleet of trucks.
      </p>

      <h3>Loan Guarantees</h3>
      <p>
        Another program is the <b>7(a) Loan Guarantee Program</b>. It is designed to assist entrepreneurs start or expand their businesses. As of 2010, the program makes up to $5 million available to small businesses through bank and non-bank institutions in the lending business. The <b>Small Business Jobs Act of 2010</b> permanently increased the maximum size of these loans from $2 million to $5 million.
      </p>

      <h3>Resource Centers Near You</h3>
      <p>
